'''Alexander Shand''' (1840&ndash;1910) was a notable New Zealand farmer, interpreter and ethnographer. He was born in [[Petone]], [[Wellington]], [[New Zealand]] in 1840.<ref name="DNZB Shand">{{DNZB|title=Alexander Shand|first= Hugh|last= Stringer|id=2s16|accessdate=15 January 2012}}</ref> His views on "sentiment" influenced [[William McDougall (psychologist)|William McDougall]]'s theory of [[instinct]].<ref>{{cite book|author=George W. Stocking|title=Malinowski, Rivers, Benedict and Others: Essays on Culture and Personality|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3rIw-XaIQU0C&pg=PA29|date=5 March 1987|publisher=Univ of Wisconsin Press|isbn=978-0-299-10733-8|page=29}}</ref>

