{{Infobox person | name = Bande Ali Mia | image = BandeAliMiaPic.jpg | alt = | caption = | birth_name = <!-- only use if different from name --> | birth_date = {{Birth date|1906|01|17}}<ref name=star>{{cite news |author=Ahmed Humayun Kabir Topu |date=2013-01-17 |title=Poet Bonde Ali's 107th birth anniversary today |url=http://www.thedailystar.net/newDesign/news-details.php?nid=265459 |newspaper=The Daily Star |accessdate=2013-01-17}}</ref> | birth_place = Narayanpur, [[Pabna]], [[East Bengal]] (now [[Bangladesh]])<ref name=star/> | death_date = {{Death date and age|1979|06|27|1906|01|17}}<ref name=star/> | death_place = [[Rajshahi]], [[Bangladesh]]<ref name=star/> | nationality = | other_names = | occupation = Poet, writer, artist, lyricist | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = | awards = [[Bangla Academy Literary Award]] (1962) }}
'''Bande Ali Mia''' ({{lang-bn|বন্দে আলী মিঞা}}; 17 January 1906{{snd}}27 June 1979) was a [[Bangladesh]]i poet.
==Early life and career== Bande was born in [[Pabna]]. He passed the entrance examination in 1923 for the Majumder Academy. He then studied painting at the Indian Art Academy in Calcutta in 1927.<ref name=bpedia/> He worked as a journalist for the magazine ''Islam Darshan''. He also taught at a Calcutta Corporation School during 1930-1950.<ref name=bpedia/> His first book, ''Char Jamai'', was published in 1927 by Calcutta Ashutosh Library.<ref name=star/> He authored a total of 84 books, most of which feature a rural setting. Another work, ''Maynamotir Char'', was published in 1931 by DM Library in [[Calcutta]]. He was the editor of the periodicals ''Bikash'' and ''Bhorer Alo''. Later he worked as a script-writer at Rajshahi Radio Station until his death in 1979.
==Legacy== Bande's poems were included in the curriculum of school level, secondary and higher secondary [[Bengali Literature]] in Bangladesh. In 1988 his admirers established the ''Kobi Bonde Ali High School''.<ref name=star/>
==Awards== *[[Bangla Academy Literary Award]] (1962)<ref name=bpedia/> *President's Award (1965) *Uttara Sahitya Majlis Padak (1977) *[[Ekushey Padak]] (1988)
==Works== Bande's noteworthy work include the following.<ref name=bpedia>{{cite book |last=Haque |first=Mahbubul |year=2012 |chapter=Mia, Bande Ali |chapter-url= http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Mia,_Bande_Ali |editor1-last=Islam |editor1-first=Sirajul |editor1-link=Sirajul Islam |editor2-last=Jamal |editor2-first=Ahmed A. |title=Banglapedia: National Encyclopedia of Bangladesh |edition=Second |publisher=[[Asiatic Society of Bangladesh]]}}</ref>
