'''Theomachist''' is a term used to refer to an individual who resists God or the [[Will of God|divine will]].<ref name=Avil>{{cite book|title=The Anglo-American Encyclopedia and Dictionary|year=1904|publisher=Avil Printing Company|isbn=0399536728}}</ref> The term comes from the [[Greek language|Greek]] words ''[[wikt:theos|theos]]'', meaning [[God]] and ''machē'', meaning [[battle]].<ref name="Evans">{{cite book|last = Evans|first = Rod|title = Unfamiliar Terms for Familiar Things|publisher = Penguin|isbn = 0399536728}}</ref> [[Karl Marx]] was considered by many to be a theomachist.<ref name="Marx">{{cite book|author = Bernice Glatzer-Rosenthal, Martha Bohachevsky-Chomiak|title = A Revolution of the Spirit: Crisis of Value in Russia, 1890-1924|publisher = Fordham Univ Press|isbn = 0823212866}}</ref> The [[atheist]]s who established the [[Cult of Reason]] in [[Revolutionary France]] have also been described with this term.<ref name=Williams>{{cite book|author=William R. Williams|title=The Conservative Principle in our Literature|date=1990-01-01|publisher=American Baptist Publication Society}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Marxism and religion]] *[[Misotheism]]
